The Stoics seem to have ad- mitted no mean between perfect wisdom or virtue and absolute folly or vice. The fool therefore was a madman, and he was

a fool who was ignorant of the truth; and this applies to all mankind, high and low, except the sage; the sage therefore is he who is perfectly acquainted with the truth, which is the Stoics’ equivalent for a vir- tuous man. This theory of virtue led to the doctrine of punishments ridiculed by Horace ἰιι the third Satire of the first book.
